node.text: Rio De Janeiro, Brazil: Witness the inspiring story of Tuany, a 23-year-old ballet dancer who started a dance company for young girls in the middle of one of Rio De Janeiro’s most dangerous favelas. She gives students hope for a better future and a safe space away from the violent world around them.

node.text: Grand Caillou/Dulac, Louisiana, U.S.A.: Meet Chief Shirell, the first female chief of her southern Louisiana tribe. Her ancestors have lived on the land for hundreds of years, and they are now expected to be among the United States’ first climate refugees. Chief Shirell can’t stop the storms, but she is impacting the legacy of her ancestors, the lives of her community today and the future of her people.

node.text: Memphis, Tennessee, U.S.A.: Meet Kayla, who has dedicated her life to helping homeless transgender women of color in Memphis, Tennessee. Having experienced homelessness and violence herself, Kayla has created a safe community for these notoriously discriminated-against people. She is building more than two dozen houses across Memphis for transgender women who need safety and a place to call home.

node.text: Photo by @nicholesobecki / With an airline eye mask and a tissue in his ears to help him stay sedated, s cheetah named Astur undergoes an intake exam at a rescue center belonging to the nonprofit Cheetah Conservation Fund, in Hargeysa, Somaliland. Cubs smuggled or intercepted from criminal rings for the illegal pet trade often get sick, typically because they’re subjected to long, grueling journeys and deprived of proper nutrition. Luckily, Astur made a full recovery after being rescued from a trafficking network through a joint effort by the Somaliland government, veterinarian Asma Bileh, and the @hornofafricaalliance, which works to counter wildlife crime in the region through community-based conservation. Our story “Cheetahs for Sale” goes inside the trafficking network that's draining Africa of its cheetah cubs—and the efforts by Somalilanders to stop the illegal trade. Click the link in Nat Geo's bio to read it. To see more of my work on humanity’s connection to the natural world, please follow @nicholesobecki.

Photo by @lucasfogliaphoto / “I’m born and bred here. Yonkers, just north of the Bronx. On 9/11, I was working at my juice bar on 23rd and 5th in Manhattan. Standing on the corner, we actually saw the tower fall. There was a massive river of humans coming up 5th Avenue. Thousands of people walking uptown, covered in dirt. We were all in shock. Right after, you couldn’t judge people, because they were all shell-shocked, upset, angry, and scared. You know, you realize there are things that are out of your control and you have to face that. So at the juice bar, we were friendlier. Like, somebody would come in and go, Yo, man, I asked for no ginger. And I’d say, You got it, buddy—I'll make a fresh one. We all needed more rope.

A week or so after the attacks the Yankees played the Mets. They wore NYPD and EMS and fire department hats. Everybody cried together. We were all New Yorkers. We all got attacked. It was like we were on one team. Everybody had a common goal. Let's all help one another and let's get back. I will never forget that ball game,” says Stephen May. 

May is pictured with his son Max in 2002, during the first summer after 9/11.  I started photographing that summer because I wanted the project to show the city healing, both in celebration and unity, and with some scars. This photograph is part of my book, Summer After, published by Stanley/Barker for the 20th anniversary of the September 11 attacks. For more, visit @lucasfogliaphoto.

node.text: Video by @joelsartore / The hauntingly beautiful Madagascar sacred ibis is most often spotted in coral pools or along lagoon shores where it can forage for food. Feeding predominantly on crustaceans, invertebrates, and plant matter, it will fully submerge its bill in mud in order to unearth well hidden prey. Video taken at the Parc Botanique et Zoologique de Tsimbazaza. To see more animals featured in the Photo Ark, follow me @joelsartore. #ibis #sacred #bird #PhotoArk #savetogether

Photo by @lucasfogliaphoto / “I don’t remember 9/11. I only remember a few years later, when I was five or six, we were at the memorial with my aunt. Her boyfriend, Sean Hanley, had been killed in one of the towers. Every time I've gone back to the memorial, I look for his name. I always felt closer to the victims, yet I was grouped in with the perpetrators.

Despite the prejudice, my father and I are still hugely patriotic. Now, I don’t love every part of America. I don’t love everything that people think here. But I do love that you’re able to think what you want. Getting an education, the freedom to marry who I want, the freedom of speech, there are just so many things that I'm thankful for, being here,” says Abu Huraira.

Abu Huraira is pictured with his father, Afzal Huraira, in 2002. I started photographing that summer because I wanted to show the city healing, in celebration and unity, and with some scars. This photograph is part of my book Summer After, published by Stanley/Barker for the 20th anniversary of the attacks. For more, visit @lucasfogliaphoto.

node.text: Photos by @williamodaniels / Congratulations to Italian fencing champion Bebe Vio, who just won a gold medal at the 2020 Tokyo Paralympic Games. Bebe lost both legs and forearms at age 11 after contracting meningitis, and risked another amputation this year after contracting a new infection in her arm. I photographed her in Italy for the magazine in 2016, prior to the Rio Paralympics, where she also won gold. Follow me @williamodaniels for human stories around the world.

node.text: Video by @lynseyaddario / The Dixie Fire rages by the Butte Lake campground in Lassen National Forest. The wildfire has burned over 900,000 acres (364,000 ha) and is the second largest fire in California history. Firefighters call these trees “widow makers” because they are often the cause of injuries and deaths among firefighters. The trees have burned so thoroughly they can fall down at any moment, or drop chunks of burned and dead tree limbs from above onto those who might be  working below. To me, these trees are the most terrifying part of covering fires, simply because of their unpredictability—when and which way they'll fall. Several times over the past 11 days, I stood photographing in a burning forest, listening to the thumps of falling trees around me and in the distance. Thank you to all the brave and tieless firefighters who are working relentlessly to fight the many fires burning across California. @calfire #dixiefire #caldorfire #wildfires #extremeweather

node.text: Photos by @celestesloman / Portrait of siblings Stephanie and Marc Crousillat, photographed at Pelham Bay Park in the Bronx. Both siblings are professional dancers who have worked together in multiple productions. In the spring I collaborated with movement director Elena Vazintaris and producer Mella Re to create a portrait series about professional dancers emerging from the pandemic. Many dancers and artists had lost their ability to perform with other artists as well as for an audience. For this project we wanted to give dancers a stage in nature, a space to be creative and feel freed from the constraints the pandemic has imposed on the performing arts.

node.text: Photo by Elliot Ross @elliotstudio / If you’ve ever driven, biked, or walked around Los Angeles, you’ve probably experienced what it’s like to find yourself suddenly blinded by intense light coming off a façade. It happened to me while driving in on the 110 freeway from the airport on my first night of this assignment to cover the demographics of shade. Traffic was moving along at a good clip, and when the glare hit, the car ahead of mine hit the brakes. Thankfully my rental car’s sensors read the situation and  automatically braked. These situations aside, this concentrated light also casts a beam of heat disproportionately onto disadvantaged neighborhoods. These areas were defined by a concept known as redlining in the first half of the 20th century, in which many neighborhoods across the country were graded A, B, C, and D (redlined)—based largely around racial makeup. Lower graded areas were comprised mostly of people of color while As and Bs consisted of majority white populations that, with the good grading, enjoyed access to zero-interest mortgages and civic investment—which includes tree cover. This legacy of codified racism is still felt today in the infrastructure and urban environments in cities across the United States. For more on this story, click the link in our bio.

Photo by David Guttenfelder @dguttenfelder / Inside Sean Sherman's Indigenous Food Lab in Minneapolis, chefs prepare duck to be distributed to elders in Indigenous communities in need across Minnesota. As 1 in 8 go hungry in the state, restaurants and food banks have banded together to salvage jobs—and served over a million meals.

Sherman and his group, aka the Sioux Chef, cook with ingredients available to Indigenous people in pre-colonial times. They offered about 36,000 meals in November and December alone, when Minnesota’s food industry shifted gears to feed the most vulnerable. 

Across the U.S., the pandemic left record numbers of people without enough food. For many, charities and neighbors have become lifelines. Check out the August issue story, "America’s Hunger Crisis" at the link in our bio.
